(36, 'Waze Â¿CÃ³mo navegar entre Datos para construir ciudades mÃ¡s inteligentes?', 'La DivisiÃ³n de Capacidad Institucional del Estado (ICS) y la Gerencia de Relaciones Externas (EXR) Invitan a participar de este BBL el 11 de abril de 12:30 a 14:00 hrs en la sala CR-2 / CCEVI  ', '1458846401.png', '', '', '', 'Miguel Guevara trabaja actualmente en el programa insignia de Waze que comparte informaciÃ³n gratuitamente con gobiernos alrededor del mundo. El programa se ha expandido alrededor del mundo e incluye ciudades de todos los tamaÃ±os. El objetivo del programa es empoderar a gobiernos usando informaciÃ³n generada en Waze. Miguel Guevara es originario de Cuernavaca, MÃ©xico. Miguel tiene una maestrÃ­a en PolÃ­ticas PÃºblicas de la Universidad de Harvard\n', '', '2016-03-24 12:06:47', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
(37, 'The impact of crime and violence on economic sector diversity', 'Presented by\nViridiana RÃ­os\nWoodrow Wilson Center\n', '', 'Wednesday April 6, 2016', '12:30-2:00 pm', 'SE-1035', '\nLiterature has focused attention on identifying whether crime and violence impact growth via changes in economic factor accumulation, i.e. reducing labor supply or increasing capital costs. Yet, much little is known as to how crime and violence may affect how economic factors are allocated. Using a unique dataset created with a text-analysis algorithm of web content, Viridianaâ€™s paper traces a decade of economic activity at the subnational level to show that increases in criminal presence and violent crime reduce economic diversification, increase sector concentration, and diminish economic complexity. An increase of 9.8% in the number of criminal organizations is enough to eliminate one economic sector. Similar effects can be felt if homicides rates increase by more than 22.5%, or if gang-related violence increases by 5.4%. By addressing the impact that crime has on the diversification of production factors, her paper takes current literature one step forward: It goes from exploring the effects of crime in the demand/supply of production factors, to analyzing its effects on economic composition.\n\nViridiana is a Ph.D. in Government from Harvard University and a research fellow at the Wilson Center in Washington, D.C. She is an expert in rule of law, security, and regional economics at Mexico. Her most current research analyzes labor markets, productivity, and development indicators at Mexico, and disentangles how violence, conflict and corruption have affected them. Before joining The Wilson Center, she was the director of MÃ©xico Â¿CÃ³mo Vamos? a start-up think tank specialized in translating research to the language of media and government officials. As public offical, she has served as adviser to Mexicoâ€™s Minister of Finance, and to Mexican Presidentâ€™s Spokesman. As researcher, she has worked with the Guggenheim Foundation of New York City, the United Nations, USAID, The World Bank, The Center for US-Mexico Studies at the University of California in San Diego, the Trans-border Institute at the University of San Diego, and Mexicoâ€™s ministries of social development (SEDESOL), education (SEP), and security (SNSP). Viridiana\'s research has been published at The New York Times, The Washington Post, and was awarded 2014â€™s American Political Science Award to the best doctoral dissertation written in the last two years. She also received Harvardâ€™s Merit Fellowship for Outstanding Research in 2011,  was selected as one of the top-12 young experts by NBERâ€™s Working Group of the Economics of Crime in 2012, and profiled at Harvard Gazette as one of the 15 Harvardâ€™s stellar graduates of 2013. At the media, Viridiana is a Sunday OpEd columnist for ExcÃ©lsior, and radio commentator at Mexico\'s 103.3 FM on Wednesdays at 3:30 pm.\n\n', '', '2016-03-29 10:53:44', 0, '', '', '', '', ''),
