(20, 12, 'Public Management Evaluation Tool (PET) o Sistema de Gestion PÃºblica (SEP)', 'The Public management Evaluation Tool (PET) evaluates five â€œpillarsâ€ of the public policies\' management cycle that are considered important for the implementation of MfDR: (i) results-based planning, (ii) results-based budgeting, (iii) public financial management (including auditing and procurement), (iv) program and project management (including the public investment system), and (v) monitoring and evaluation of public management. These pillars are broken down into components that track the maturity of institutional systems. The components are in turn composed of indicators and minimum requirements that these systems must have in an MfDR environment. All of these measures (minimum requirements, indicators, components, and pillars) are scored on a scale from 0 to 5, where a 5 indicates an ideal institutional situation.\r\n\r\n', 'Link', 'https://mydata.iadb.org/Reform-Modernization-of-the-State/Public-management-Evaluation-Tool/c89t-dh9r', '2015-07-06 09:16:51', '#9C0000'),
(21, 12, 'Civil Service Development Index (CSDI) o Ãndice de Desarrollo del Servicio Civil (IDSC): ', 'Results of the Civil Service Development Index (CSDI), obtained from diagnostics of the institutional quality of civil service systems in 16 Latin American countries. The IDB supported the design of a methodology that evaluates critical points to assess the civil services and carried out country evaluations in 2004. Between 2011 and 2013, a second group of diagnostics second group of diagnostics were completed (with the support of the Inter-American Development Bank, and in the case of Central American countries and Dominican Republic with the support of the Spanish Agency for International Cooperation and Development â€“AECID- and the Central American Integration System-SICA). During the first assessment, 93 critical points were identified; each of those fed a subsystem and an index. In 2010 the methodology was simplified to 33 critical points and the base line was recalibrated to ensure comparability. The methodology is based in the identification of critical points that feed 8 subsystems: 1. Human Resources Planning, 2. Work Organization, 3. Employment management, 4. Performance management, 5. Compensation management, 6. Development management, 7. Human and social relations management, 8. HR Function organization; and 5 indexes: 1. Efficiency, 2. Merit, 3. Structural consistency, 4. Functional capacity, and 5. Integrating capacity.\r\n', 'Link ', 'https://mydata.iadb.org/Reform-Modernization-of-the-State/Civil-Service-Development-Index/ddw5-db4y', '2015-07-06 09:16:51', '#085294'),
(23, 17, 'Descarga el estudio completo', 'Este nuevo estudio del BID muestra cÃ³mo los gobiernos reconocen la importancia de este crecimiento y se involucran cada dÃ­a mÃ¡s aprovechando el potencial de las redes sociales y el anÃ¡lisis de datos. En AmÃ©rica Latina, los gobernantes promueven la participaciÃ³n activa de sus administraciones en las redes sociales y comienzan a ver la relevancia de una escucha mÃ¡s activa de lo que los ciudadanos tienen para decir en la construcciÃ³n de nuevas formas de gobernar.', 'Estudio completo', 'http://publications.iadb.org/handle/11319/6952', '2015-07-21 13:03:09', '#9CC6EF'),
(24, 21, 'Objectives', '1. Introduce to the fundamentals of first-person storytelling and how to use these stories to promote understanding, motivate, and rally support and buy-in for various projects and initiatives.\r\n2.	Practice constructing narrative and reflecting upon the characteristics of well-told stories.\r\n3.	Enhance IFDâ€™s storytelling culture and its ability to tell stories.\r\n4.	Discuss ideas on opportunities for applying storytelling as a technique at IFD.', '', '', '2015-09-23 09:18:11', ''),
(25, 21, 'Agenda:', '10am-12pm \r\nUnderstanding Storytelling: A two-hour training for 20-25 participants. At the end of this session, participants will be instructed to think think about story idea and apply the skills they just learned to come up with a 2 minute story they will share with the group after lunch.\r\n\r\n12pm-1pm \r\nLunch Break\r\n\r\n1pm- 3pm \r\nStories in Action: Each participant will have the opportunity to share a two-minute story and receive on-the-spot coaching from the trainers.\r\n', '', '', '2015-09-23 09:18:11', ''),
(26, 25, 'x', 'It has become clichÃ©â€”but no less trueâ€”to say that the Internet, and information technology more generally, have affected the way we work, play, and engage with the world. On a broader scale, IT and the Internet also have the potential to dramatically affect economic development in positive and negative ways. Its many benefits may include facilitating citizen interactions with each other and their governments, promoting entrepreneurship, making government more efficient, and helping firms better participate in a global economy. \r\n\r\nExperts from leading think tanks, academia, government, international organizations and the private sector, including Google, Facebook and Microsoft will provide an overview of major issues facing Internet development and the use of new technologies. Specifically, they will give participants a framework for thinking about these issues in the context of economic development. Session will include a tutorial explaining the underlying technology of wired and wireless Internet connectivity, discussions of broadband build out and adoption, the impact of applications like mobile health and big data, and presentations of uses of the Internet and technology in development projects.', '', '', '2015-11-17 15:43:06', ''),
