(52, 46, 'New Dataset of Housing Indicators | FMM & HUD | Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Mexico', 'Quality of Life Indicators - Home Sweet Home', 'This dataset is the result of the efforts of a working group made up of the IDB, Habitat for Humanity International, the World Bank, Cities Alliance, the Information Network Housing Finance (HOFINET), and UN-Habitat.  It showcases indicators compiled from four global databases: HOFINET, the Global Housing Policy Indicators (GHPI) of Habitat for Humanity, the United Nations Compendium of Housing Statistics (UNCHS), and the World Bank World Development Indicators (WB-WDI). Data from national census agencies has also been included, as well as indicators obtained from specific surveys collected in areas where data was not available.\r\n \r\nThis dataset includes information from Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, and Mexico.  The indicators are presented in a format that allows for comparison across the national, municipal , and local levels. The data gathered attempts to provide answers to five questions:\r\n<ul>\r\n(i)                  Is housing affordable and financeable?\r\n(ii)                Is housing adequate?\r\n(iii)               Is housing connected?\r\n(iv)              Is housing green and sustainable\r\n(v)                Is housing a secure asset?\r\n </ul> \r\nThe dataset contains the most recent data available to the working group and its partners.  If there is no data given for an indicator, then one can assume that there is no data available to the working group for that specific indicator. Indicators requiring monetary amounts are displayed in UDS dollars for comparison purposes.  The following indicates potential limitations in comparing the indicators across levels.  This is not an exhaustive list and it is the responsibility of the user to determine if it is appropriate to compare: the dataset contains the most recent data available to the working group and partner organizations.  The year 2015 was used for laws and regulations that are still in effect.  Some indicators are calculated from metadata contained in other sources.  Notes and sources are included for every data point, which explains where the data is from and if necessary how it is calculated.  Some indicators have sub-indicators.  These sub indicators are included to provide more information but are based on data availability and may not be consistent across each level or country.', '', 'https://mydata.iadb.org/Urban-Development-and-Housing/Dataset-of-Housing-Indicators/s8qq-iq5k', '2016-05-23 09:26:06', 'See full dataset'),
